{"0": "How to Do Man-on-the-Street Interviews", "1": "The man-on-the-street interview is an interview in which a reporter hits the streets with a cameraman to interview people on the spot.", "2": "For new reporters, this can seem like a challenging task.", "3": "But with these tips, your first man-on-the-street interview experience can be easy.", "4": "When your boss or professor sends you out to do man-on-the-street interviews for a story, think about the topic and develop a list of about ten general questions related to it.", "5": "For example, if your topic is about environmental problems in America, you might ask, \"Why do you think environmental protection is important in America?\"", "6": "If you don't own a camera, you can buy one.", "7": "Hit the streets with confidence.", "8": "As you approach people, be polite.", "9": "Say, \"Excuse me, I work for XYZ News, and I was wondering if you could share your opinion about this topic.\"", "10": "This is a quick way to get people to warm up to you.", "11": "Move on to the next person if someone tells you she is not interested.", "12": "Don't get discouraged.", "13": "Limit your time.", "14": "Each interview that you get on the street shouldn't be longer than ten minutes.", "15": "As soon as you get the answer you need, move on to the next person.", "16": "Make sure that as you go from interview to interview, you are getting a variety of answers.", "17": "If everyone is giving you the same answer, you won't be able to use it.", "18": "A safe number of interviews to conduct is about six to ten.", "19": "That number of interviews should give you all the answers you need.", "20": "If your news station or school requires interviewees to sign release forms to appear on the air, don't leave work without them."}